name: Aurorus Borealis
crin_comments: Sounds like an odd mashup of the HD600 and the Clear, in a good way.

name: HEDDphone
crin_comments: An interesting in-between of DD and estat timbre, though tuning around the lower midrange may be off.

name: Nectar Hive
crin_comments: Some spiciness in the treble that is HD800-esque, but with a better midrange presentation.

name: Hifiman Jade II
crin_comments: Suffers from typical estat timbre and bass extension issues, but otherwise a very resolving and well-tuned headphone.

name: Stax SR-007 (Mk2.5)
crin_comments: Arguably the least wonky-sounding of the mainstream Staxes, with resolution just shy of the flagship 009.

name: Sennheiser HD600
crin_comments: The legendary neutral reference. Slightly better clarity and imaging than the HD650.

name: Audio Technica ATH-R70x
crin_comments: Excellent imaging. Mostly neutral/flat tuning with an ever-so-slight tilt towards warmth.

name: Hifiman Edition X V2
crin_comments: Excellent tonal balance though limited by blunted notes and resolution.

name: Stax SR-Lambda Pro
crin_comments: One of the original Lambda models, and arguably the best tuned of the Lambda-styled Staxes.

name: Hifiman Arya
crin_comments: High resolution planar that may be a little peaky in the treble for some.

name: Hifiman HE1000se
crin_comments: Basically a brighter and slightly shoutier version of the OG; may be a little too intense for some.

name: Hifiman Shangri-La Jr
crin_comments: A tad too shouty for my tastes, but far less offensive tonal characteristics than the average estat.

name: Shure SRH440
crin_comments: Closest thing to Harman thus far. Comes with a small upper treble spike and lacking raw resolution.

name: AKG K371
crin_comments: Expectedly Harman tuning but lacks a bit of bite in the upper midrange for "true Harman".

name: Hifiman HE400i (2020)
crin_comments: Well-executed reference-ish tuning with a slight treble emphasis.

name: AKG K701
crin_comments: The brightest and arguably harshest of the K7-- lineup, but still very competent overall.

name: Sennheiser HD560S
crin_comments: Well-balanced tonality with good bass extension, just slightly hot in the upper-mids and treble.

name: Hifiman Deva
crin_comments: Probably the most "mellow" of the Hifiman planars with the least resolving ability.

name: Sennheiser HD660S
crin_comments: An even darker HD6X0. A comparatively muffled mess just barely propped up by its decent resolving ability.

name: Beyerdynamic DT880 Pro (32Ω)
crin_comments: Certainly a "mini-HD800" in terms of tonality only, however still far inferior in technical ability.

name: HarmonicDyne Zeus
crin_comments: A rare combination of a warm-focused tonality with decent technicalities.

name: Sennheiser Momentum 3 Wireless
crin_comments: A massive improvement over its predecessor. Limited resolution and potentially intense tonality.

name: Beyerdynamic DT990 Pro (250Ω)
crin_comments: Pretty bog-standard V-shaped response with forward upper-midrange and decently high resolution.

name: Beyerdynamic TYGR 300 R
crin_comments: Very reminiscent of the DT990.

name: Stax SR-L300
crin_comments: Generally pleasing tuning, though a little honky and fatiguing in the treble.

name: ZMF Aeolus
crin_comments: Tonally, a vast improvement over the Aeolus with stock pads, bringing in extra clarity and bite.

name: Hifiman HE6se
crin_comments: Comes with an odd midrange dip. It's no HE6 replacement for sure.

name: Hifiman HE560 (V1)
crin_comments: Slight wonkiness around the lower midrange, but otherwise a capable planar headphone.

name: Final D8000 Pro
crin_comments: Highly resolving headphone with solid imaging capabilities, limited by its somewhat wonky tonality.

name: Final Audio D8000
crin_comments: High treble-to-midrange contrast makes things sound shrill and borderline-sibilant.

name: RAAL-requisite SR1a
crin_comments: Weak, limp bass is the killing blow for what is an otherwise highly resolving and decently-tuned earspeaker.

name: Focal Stellia
crin_comments: "Harman-inspired" tuning works decently well, though a myriad of small quirks ultimately screws its tonal balance.

name: Stax SR-L700
crin_comments: Probably the most balanced tuning of the L-series, with the usual e-stat technicalities.

name: ZMF Verite Closed
crin_comments: Far more tonally balanced than its open counterpart, whilst retaining its reverberant staging.

name: Audio Technica ATH-ADX5000
crin_comments: Clean, open sound reminsicent of the HD800, with a bit of midbass bloat and upper midrange shoutiness.

name: Stax SR-L300 Limited
crin_comments: Honkier version of the standard L300.

name: Sony MDR-SA5000
crin_comments: Surprisingly competent for a decades-old set. Midrange is a little uneven but beats out many other modern TOTLs.

name: Hifiman HE5
crin_comments: The original Hifiman. Midrange is a little too scooped out but remains competitive even today.

name: Denon AH-D5000
crin_comments: The usual "Foster biodyna dynamics" are at play here, with a somewhat fatiguing treble spike.

name: Kennerton Odin
crin_comments: Generally "okay" tonality with some odd dips here and there. Lacking serious extension for a planar.

name: Kennerton Thror
crin_comments: Kind of a "nothing headphone"; not bad, not great, just good enough to be okay.

name: Focal Radiance
crin_comments: Probably the best of the closed-back Focals. Some tuning refinements over the Stellia, though technically limited.

name: Focal Clear Mg
crin_comments: Lacks upper mids and resolution compared to its predecessor.

name: Audeze LCD-XC
crin_comments: Definitely the least Audeze-sounding Audeze. A little quirky tonally, but nothing too offensive.

name: Focal Elear
crin_comments: Subdued upper midrange with the odd treble spike makes this a weird headphone to listen to.

name: Meze Empyrean
crin_comments: Bland and unexciting tuning with compressed staging and generally underperforming technicalities.

name: Koss KSC75
crin_comments: Non-existent sub-bass and poor resolution. But it's so well-tuned you may not even care.

name: Sivga Phoenix
crin_comments: A fairly competent warm-neutral monitor slightly held back by limited detail retrieval.

name: Audio Technica ATH-M70x
crin_comments: The most neutral of the M-series. Good tonality but still suffers from narrow imaging.

name: Sennheiser HD25 Plus
crin_comments: Punchy, energetic sound with decently balanced tonality. A pretty good beat-tracking monitor.

name: BLON B20
crin_comments: Basically a darker planar HD6X0, with equally closed-in staging and lacking the final resolving edge.

name: Massdrop x Koss ESP/95X
crin_comments: Good resolving ability and imaging, marred by its odd and honky midrange.

name: ASTRO A40 TR
crin_comments: Middling technicalities, but for a gaming headphone its tonality is surprisingly balanced.

name: Audio Technica ATH-M40x
crin_comments: Well-balanced tonality with disappointing detailing and claustrophobic imaging.

name: Moondrop Void
crin_comments: Slightly midbass/lower-mid emphasised with good tonal balance, if rather "cheap"-sounding.

name: E-MU Walnut
crin_comments: Tonality is somewhat off with peaks and dips here and there, but overall not a bad sounding headphone.

name: Hifiman HE500
crin_comments: Perhaps the warmest of the Hifiman lineup. Not the most resolving.

name: Audeze LCD-24
crin_comments: A slight tonal improvement over the LCD-4, but also comes with a slight hit in resolution.

name:
Abyss Diana Phi
Abyss Diana V2
crin_comments: Needs a little more upper midrange to balance out the honkiness. Good dynamic performance especially in the bass.

name: Audeze LCD-X (2021)
crin_comments: Tonally, a massive improvement over the previous version(s) though with the usual pitfalls of the Audeze house sound.

name: Denon AH-D5200
crin_comments: Probably the least wonky of the new Denons. Suffers from some mid-bass bloat.

name: Beyerdynamic DT1990 Pro
crin_comments: An intense sound given its significant treble boost, but countered by a smooth lower-midrange bump.

name: Audeze LCD-GX
crin_comments: As a gaming headphone, possibly the best technically though with the usual pitfalls of the Audeze house sound.

name: Audeze LCD-2 Closed-back
crin_comments: Not the worst Audeze in terms of tonality, but its tuning still doesn't live up to its technical capabilities.

name: Audeze LCD-2 Classic
crin_comments: Classic Audeze combo of solid resolution with a confusing lack of upper midrange.

name: Apple AirPods Max
crin_comments: Great tonality, sub-focused bass emphasis, bassy without being muddy. Average imaging and resolution.

name: ZMF Verite
crin_comments: Excellent resolution unfortunately marred by suppressed harmonics and a harsh upper-midrange.

name: ES Lab ES-1a
crin_comments: Seems inspired by the tuning of the SR-009 with some minor improvements, though not enough to call it "good".

name: Fostex TR80
crin_comments: A very well-tuned monitor-style headphone, if heavily bottlenecked by narrow imaging and blunt hits.

name: AKG K612 Pro
crin_comments: Basically dead-neutral tuning, emphasis on "dead". Strong all-rounder whose only fault is not having that "wow-factor".

name: Sennheiser HD650/HD6XX
crin_comments: The legendary neutral reference. "Veiled" with a warm tilt (in comparison to HD600), and pretty terrible at imaging.

name: Shure SRH840
crin_comments: Extremely well-executed V-shaped tuning with no erronous peaks or dips. More mid-bassy than sub-bassy.

name: Hifiman Sundara
crin_comments: Solid tuning with a little treble spiciness for the daring. One of the better midrange planars out there.

name: AKG K702
crin_comments: Slightly more upper-mid-forward (read: shoutier) version of the K612.

name: Hifiman Ananda
crin_comments: One of the best tuned headphones available, only limited by its raw resolving ability.

name: Fostex TH610
crin_comments: The most neutral of the Foster biodyna models. If you want a little more balance than the Teaks.

name: E-MU Teak
crin_comments: Excellent dynamics with one of the best bass I've heard in a headphone, though the midrange can be a little harsh.

name: Shure SRH1540
crin_comments: Almost "Harman" tuning with some undesirable mid-bass bloat.

name: Stax SR-404
crin_comments: Similar tuning to that of the Lambda Pro. Sonically identical between 404 and 404LE.

name: Stax SR-507
crin_comments: Similar tuning to that of the Lambda Pro.

name: Hifiman HE6
crin_comments: Clean, resolving yet intense sound scratches the detail itch but is a little too edgy for long listens.

name: Stax SR-4070
crin_comments: Surprisingly wide and spacious soundstage for a closed-back. Good low-end extension but rather shouty.

name: ZMF Auteur
crin_comments: Very pleasant tonality but lacking that last bit of definition for true top-tier status.

name: Sennheiser HD800/HD800S
crin_comments: Arguably the king of soundstage and raw detail, though at the cost of its infamous treble spike.

name: Beyerdynamic T70
crin_comments: Treble peak may offend some, but otherwise very well balanced and natural tonality with decent technicalities.

name: MrSpeakers Ether C
crin_comments: Forward, in-your-face sound that's shouty and thin at the same time. A good reference for "true DF neutral".

name: Stax SR-L500
crin_comments: Generally pleasing tuning with a little honkiness in the centre-midrange.

name: Sennheiser HD599
crin_comments: A little too sharp, a little too midbassy, but overall not the most offensive headphone out there.

name: Massdrop x AKG K7XX
crin_comments: A more bloated-sounding K712.

name: HarmonicDyne Helios
crin_comments: Lack of bass extension is its biggest dealbreaker of what would be an otherwise solid headphone.

name: 1MORE MK801
crin_comments: Smooth, generally pleasing tonality throughout with no offensive characteristics.

name: Sennheiser HD579
crin_comments: More or less a HD599 with slightly worse resolution.

name: Acoustic Research AR-H1
crin_comments: A tempered, almost bright-leaning planar (but not quite). Decent tonality and technical ability.

name: Beyerdynamic T5p (1st Gen)
crin_comments: Choppy midrange response is its biggest turnoff, but otherwise a decent V-shaped headphone.

name: Timsok TS-1024
crin_comments: Somewhat warm midrange plagued with sharp and offensive treble.

name: Sendy Aiva
crin_comments: A slightly worse-tuned B20, kinda.

name: AKG K712 Pro
crin_comments: Sizeable mid-bass bloat that's barely reigned in by an equally sizeable upper-midrange emphasis.

name: Fostex TH7
crin_comments: Fairly neutral monitor-style headphone with poor imaging and detail retrieval.

name: Sony MDR-Z1R
crin_comments: Holes in the midrange. Big spike in the treble. Strangely disjointed soundstage. Decently resolving.

name: Fostex TH900
crin_comments: Spicy sibilance and bloated bass are disappointments in what is otherwise an extremely dynamic headphone.

name: DCA Aeon 2 Closed
crin_comments: Passable tonality with dulled and blunted transients make for lacklustre detailing.

name: Stax SR-009/SR-009S
crin_comments: Detail and resolution worthy of being called "the best", marred by the tonally-off midrange.

name: Audeze LCD-4
crin_comments: A classic example of a highly resolving yet wonky sounding headphone. Needs more upper midrange.

name: Sony MDR-MA900
crin_comments: Imaging as expected of an earspeaker configuration; surprisingly good tonality and expected bad extension.

name: Fostex TH909
crin_comments: A slightly more balanced TH900 with similar sibilance issues.

name: Neumann NDH 20
crin_comments: Feels like an attempt at Harman but ultimately missing the mark in the midrange tuning.

name: Rosson RAD-0
crin_comments: Middling technicalities with suppressed upper midrange.

name: Sony MDR-1AM2
crin_comments: Harman-ish tuning with a strong mid-bass presence and piercing upper treble response.

name: Abyss AB-1266 Phi
crin_comments: Sinfully addictive bass and treble reponse, but the midrange tonality needs a lot of work.

name: Audeze LCD-MX4
crin_comments: Classic Audeze combo of solid resolution with a confusing lack of upper midrange.

name: Hifiman HE5SE
crin_comments: Strong contender for an excellent headphone, if not for the inexplicable hole in the mids.

name: Sony MDR-CD380
crin_comments: Shouty and thin-sounding, though surprisingly competent imaging ability.

name: Hifiman Susvara
crin_comments: Subtle refinements to the already-great HE1000 makes this arguably the best planar in the world.

name: Sennheiser HE-1
crin_comments: Mostly neutral, slight bass lift, highly resolving and natural both in tone and timbre. The world's best headphone.

name: Focal Utopia
crin_comments: Solid tuning with close to top-tier resolution. An inoffensive all-rounder that lives up to its reputation.

name: Hifiman HE1000 (V2)
crin_comments: A planar that comes unnervingly close estat speed, but not quite. Solid technicalities with excellent tone.

name: 7Hz Timeless
crin_comments: Easily the best-tuned planar IEM by a country mile, the Timeless is also no slouch on the technical front.

name: ThieAudio Oracle
crin_comments: Functionally similar to the Clairvoyance with slight cutbacks in overall clarity and resolution.

name: Softears RSV
crin_comments: Very well-balanced tonality with surprisingly good timbre, though slightly lacking definition.

name: ThieAudio Monarch
crin_comments: Neutral with bass boost

name: Moondrop S8
crin_comments: More faithful to the Harman target compared to the A8, with a smoother bass response.

name: StereoPravda SB7
crin_comments: Technically proficient but marred by a sharp timbre. Interesting concept.

name: 64 Audio A/U12t
crin_comments: Amazing bass (for a BA), top-tier resolution and detail-oriented signature.

name: Hidition Violet
crin_comments: Strong sub-bass presence, slightly cut-back upper mids. A fun IEM through and through.

name: Empire Ears Odin
crin_comments: A Legend X with the bass properly controlled and the resolution one step higher.

name: Vision Ears Erlkonig
crin_comments: Good tonality, high resolution and an overall decent all-rounder.

name: Moondrop Blessing 2
crin_comments: Very well tuned from bass to treble, perhaps lacking in the last octaves of extension.

name: Moondrop A8
crin_comments: An odd but surprisingly decent take on the Harman signature, with added midbass compared to the S8.

name: qdc Anole V14
crin_comments: Rather bassy even in stock form; fun and engaging, though at the expense of sheer technical performance.

name: Kumitate KL-Sirius
crin_comments: Excellent technical ability, well tuned with a dash of Japanese flavour.

name: Etymotic ER4XR
crin_comments: A more mainstream tuning of the ER4S/SR with slightly boosted bass.

name: Sony IER-M7
crin_comments: Balanced across the board, though doesn't seem to excel in any particular area.

name: Vision Ears Elysium
crin_comments: First decent implementation of Sonion's EST tweeters.

name: Kiwi Ears Orchestra
crin_comments: Very well-tuned reference-y signature with a mild bass and treble emphasis for added energy.

name: Ultimate Ears Reference Monitor (UERM)
crin_comments: The benchmark of an era, dead-flat with an upper treble boost

name: ThieAudio Clairvoyance
crin_comments: Inoffensive, pleasant tuning specialising in extremely balanced tonality and bass control.

name: JVC HA-FW10000
crin_comments: Intense and shouty DF-style signature with solid resolution.

name: Sony IER-M9
crin_comments: Neutral tonality, highly coherent and decent detail pickup. The all-rounder of the IER lineup.

name: qdc 8SS
crin_comments: The neutral "studio monitor" of qdc's 8-series of IEMs, lacking a bit in overall extension.

name: Hidition NT8
crin_comments: Coloured neutral kind of sound that works better with Asian genres.

name: Drop + JVC HA-FDX1
crin_comments: Highly technical sound with a clean, well-tuned neutral signature.

name: Moondrop Blessing
crin_comments: All rounder that comes the closest to the Harman Target.

name: PEARS SH3
crin_comments: Great detail pickup and solid all-rounder, perhaps a little strident.

name: Empire Ears ESR Mk2
crin_comments: Possibly the most pleasant-sounding of the Empire Ears lineup with decent detailing to boot.

name: Kumitate KL-Focus
crin_comments: Selectable bass response with the rest of the FR following a more "Japanese reference" tuning.

name: 64 Audio Tia Trio
crin_comments: A more correct sounding version of the Fourte with slight cutbacks in staging and sheer resolution.

name: Softears Turii
crin_comments: Resolving and fairly well-tuned dynamic-driver IEM.

name: 64 Audio A/U18 Tzar
crin_comments: A rather simple and "mainstream" tuning refined to a high level.

name: 64 Audio Nio
crin_comments: A decent bassy set with the m15/m20 modules, but really shines with the mX modules.

name: Hidition Waltz
crin_comments: Neutral-fun signature that works both as a reference monitor and a rock-out IEM.

name: Shure KSE1200
crin_comments: Easily at the top in terms of resolution and definition, but comes with a big treble spike and slightly odd mids.

name: ThieAudio Excalibur
crin_comments: Probably the weakest of the ThieAudio tribrids, but still great on its own.

name: Lime Ears Model X
crin_comments: Technically capable IEM that goes from decently neutral to warm and smooth in a pinch.

name: See Audio Neo
crin_comments: Well-balanced tonality with good resolution; emphasised bass with good control.

name: InEar SD5
crin_comments: Excels in timbre reproduction and has an overall pleasant signature.

name: Noble K10 Encore
crin_comments: Reference oriented sound focused on technicalities.

name: Noble Katana
crin_comments: Like the K10, except with less bass.

name: Elysian Poseidon
crin_comments: Good, inoffensive midrange tone and bass tuning, marred by the lack of low-level detailing.

name: Empire Ears Legend X
crin_comments: High resolution hybrid flawed only by lack of control in the bass regions.

name: Vision Ears VE8
crin_comments: Extremely coherent signature with a pleasing tuning and high technicalities.

name: Empire Ears Legend X SE
crin_comments: A more upper-mid-forward variation of the original Legend X, which could come off as slightly more mid-recessed.

name: Massdrop x Noble K10
crin_comments: Very safe tuning, almost to the point of boredom. Does nothing wrong but nothing right either.

name: Moondrop Variations
crin_comments: Sub-bass-focused signature with Moondrop's clean tuning makes this one of the best $500 tribrids.

name: Sennheiser IE600
crin_comments: Well-tuned mids, powerful yet controlled sub-bass, with highly extended (and somewhat spicy) treble.

name: Softears RS10
crin_comments: A little shouty and intense but very resolving and well-defined. A somewhat refined Moondrop S8.

name: Sony IER-Z1R
crin_comments: Extended yet natural treble, realistic sub-bass focus and spacious imaging capabilities.

name: Hidition NT6
crin_comments: If Etymotic made a multi-BA IEM, this would be the closest to that dream

name: qdc 8SL/Gemini/Anole VX
crin_comments: Reference tuning with good tonality and top-level resolution. Similar tunings across top tier models.

name: Moondrop Chu
crin_comments: An extremely well-tuned neutral IEM with a slightly bright and metallic tilt.

name:
Lypertek PurePlay Z3 2.0
(PurePlay Z3)
(Tevi)
crin_comments: Probably the closest thing to an ER2XR in TWS form.

name: Samsung Galaxy Buds
crin_comments: A surprisingly well-tuned TWS with the technical chops to boot.

name: JVC HA-FD01
crin_comments: Upper-mid forward signature can get a little shouty, but a decently technical DD still.

name: JVC HA-FD02
crin_comments: Upper-mid forward signature can get a little shouty, but a decently technical DD still.

name: FAudio Minor
crin_comments: Well-balanced tonality and tuning, held back by middling technicalities.

name: Tanchjim Darling
crin_comments: A tad shouty but with excellent imaging performance.

name: Libratone Track Air Plus
crin_comments: Deep and focused sub-bass response with a surprisingly balanced midrange tonality.

name: FiiO FH5
crin_comments: Stellar bass response and decent technical ability, not much to fault.

name: Sennheiser IE300
crin_comments: Fairly mainstream tuning with a treble response that's well done given its emphasis.

name: DUNU SA6
crin_comments: Tonality reminiscent of the Anole VX, though not up to the same level of technicalities.

name: Tansio Mirai TSMR-12 "Zodiac"
crin_comments: Very clean, monitor/reference-style sound.

name: Acoustune HS1650
crin_comments: Well textured and energetic with a sub-bass focus.

name: Acoustune HS1670
crin_comments: Metallic and shrill timbre makes this hard to enjoy.

name: ThieAudio Voyager 14 (V14)
crin_comments: Evokes a qdc-ish house sound, though stumbles in both tuning refinement and technicalities.

name: Fearless Lancelot
crin_comments: Rather generic tuning with no redeeming qualities for its price and status.

name: Acoustune HS1695Ti
crin_comments: Sub-bass focused emphasis balanced out by midtreble peaks.

name: Moondrop Aria
crin_comments: A cheaper Starfield.

name: Moondrop Starfield
crin_comments: A cheaper KXXS.

name: Moondrop KXXS
crin_comments: Well-tuned single DD with proper timbre and decent technicalities.

name: Aya Siren
crin_comments: Very neutral, very well-tuned, though not very snappy in the treble.

name: Shuoer x HBB EJ07M Kinda Lava Edition
Unique Melody Martian
crin_comments: Well-tuned hybrid with excellent bass response and smooth midrange.

name: HYLA TE-5T
crin_comments: Very Japanese-sounding with a massive upper harmonic focus, too much for many genres.

name: Unique Melody Maestro V2
crin_comments: It's... there. An IEM that exists. Hard to find words for this one.

name: Final Audio A8000
crin_comments: Technically strong but going too far with the treble emphasis.

name: Oriolus Percivali
crin_comments: Lacking body and very thin in the notes. Not recommended for sub-tenor instruments.

name: Oriolus Mellianus
crin_comments: Thin and sterile signature that isn't the most natural, but still technically proficient.

name: Jomo Trinity Brass
crin_comments: The warmer of the Trinity models, sacrificing technical ability for a more pleasing and smoother tone.

name: Jomo Samba
crin_comments: Lively and engaging with big clarity and detail, perhaps too much for some

name: Moondrop Solis
crin_comments: A good implementation of the EST drivers with Moondrop's signature tuning specialties.

name: Prisma Azul
crin_comments: A well-balanced neutral monitor bottlenecked by sheer resolution and narrow imaging performance.

name: DUNU Luna
crin_comments: Needs more work on the tuning front.

name: Dita Dream
crin_comments: Excellent resolution and detail let down by its metallic tonality and thin midrange

name: See Audio Yume
crin_comments: Excellent tuning with impeccable bass control, though with mushy transients and lacking detail.

name: Fearless S8F/S8Pro
crin_comments: Tonally pleasing V-shaped signature on a solid technical foundation.

name: AAW ASH
crin_comments: Smooth tonal balance with decent technicalities.

name: qdc Anole V6
crin_comments: The more mid-centric of the Anole brothers. Better technicalities but worse timbre.

name: Campfire Andromeda (2020)
crin_comments: Basically an Andromeda without the treble spike and slightly boosted midrange.

name: Campfire Andromeda (S)
crin_comments: Highly coherent, easy-to-love tuning and spacious headstage

name: See Audio Kaguya
crin_comments: Somewhat mid-scooped, decent bass and treble extension though with underwhelming resolving ability.

name: Softears Cerberus
crin_comments: Lacking definition in the treble, otherwise a decently balanced tribrid IEM.

name: Ultimate Ears UE4 Pro
crin_comments: Pretty much a mini-UE7.

name: A&K T8iE
crin_comments: Hard-to-dislike tuning with excellent clarity and resolution.

name: Samsung Galaxy Buds+
crin_comments: Tuned even closer to the Harman IE target compared to the original.

name: Etymotic ER4PT
crin_comments: Slightly rolled off treble with good detail and resolution, though imaging is too two-dimensional.

name: DUNU EST 112
crin_comments: Good tonality, though the treble extension is its big Achille's Heel.

name: Shuoer EJ07
crin_comments: Tuned almost Etymotic-like but with underwhelming treble extension bottlenecking it all.

name: Empire Ears Hero
crin_comments: Well-controlled bass emphasis with a less-well-controlled treble emphasis makes this hard to appreciate.

name: ThieAudio Legacy 4 (L4)
crin_comments: Well-tuned if technically lacking in comparison. Could use some more power in the bass.

name: Moondrop Kanas Pro
crin_comments: Somewhat Harman-esque in tuning, not the best in terms of resolution.

name: Unique Melody Merlin V2
crin_comments: Very tasteful and coherent tuning, if lacking in sheer resolution.

name: 64 Audio A6t
crin_comments: Very warm and intimate presentation, though overall tonal balance is somewhat preserved.

name: Audiosense DT200
crin_comments: Excellent tonality. Just excellent tuning overall.

name: 64 Audio tia Fourte
crin_comments: Unique sound; high clarity and bass response with immensely wide staging, held back by a wonky tonality.

name: 64 Audio tia Fourte Noir
crin_comments: A bassier and warmer Fourte though also strangely sharper and less technical.

name: Sony MDR-EX1000
crin_comments: Outstanding imaging and detail retrieval though can be intense to listen to.

name: Dita Sakura 71
crin_comments: Very upper-mid forward. Would appreciate the shout being dialed way down.

name: Sony XBA-N3
crin_comments: Exceptional tonal balance only limited by its slightly smoothed over definition

name: Kumitate KL-Corona
crin_comments: Well-tuned with somewhat disappointing technical performance.

name: Moondrop Crescent
crin_comments: Well-executed V-ish signature that's neither harsh nor bloated.

name: Aya Trident
crin_comments: Somewhat strange tuning that seems to try to do everything, but results in a slightly wonky tonality.

name: Moondrop Illumination
crin_comments: Well-tuned with natural timbre, ultimately marred by subpar detail retrieval and definition.

name: Fearless La Hire
crin_comments: Well-tuned neutral-style monitor with subpar treble extension.

name: iBasso IT07
crin_comments: More similar to its predecessor the IT04, with more bass and less treble.

name: qdc 5SH
crin_comments: Fun, lively signature that retains high levels of performance.

name: Kinera Nanna 2.0
crin_comments: Bass is a tad uncontrolled and the mids could use more refinement. The original is arguably superior.

name: AKG N5005
crin_comments: Amazing bass control only let down by plastic timbre.

name: Unique Melody Mirage
crin_comments: Tonally-balanced, technically acceptable, nothing much to criticise though no big praises either.

name: Empire Ears Vantage
crin_comments: A Legend-X-mini, essentially. Nice alternative on a "budget".

name: Sony Justear XJE-MH2 "Club"
crin_comments: Nice, pleasant signature that is reminiscent of a more textured HS1551.

name: Ultimate Ears UE18+ Pro Gen 2
crin_comments: Somewhat reference tuning with emphasis on tonal accuracy and naturalness

name: Kumitate KL-REF Type S
crin_comments: Triggers uncanny valley hard. Presentation is always slighty off in some area that I can't pinpoint.

name: Intime Sora
crin_comments: Well controlled bass boost with slightly skewed tonality. Potential is there.

name: Tanchjim Cora
crin_comments: Well-controlled bass boost, though coupled with a slightly odd midrange tonality.

name: Moondrop Sparks
crin_comments: A tad too shouty and lacking low-level detail, but nothing too egregious as a whole.

name: Tin HiFi T4
crin_comments: A worthy successor to the legendary GR07.

name: Acoustune HS1300
crin_comments: A less warm, slightly brighter version of the coveted HS1551.

name: Sony WF-1000XM3
crin_comments: Proper tonality, solid technicalities yet with a consumer-friendly signature.

name: Sony MDR-EX800ST/MDR7550
crin_comments: A more forgiving, warmer version of the EX1000.

name: JVC HA-FW03
crin_comments: Slightly shouty but balanced out by a warm mid-bass hump. Lacking overall definition.

name: FiiO FD5
crin_comments: Pretty standard V-shaped tuning though surprisingly proficient in technicalities.

name: qdc Neptune
crin_comments: Tuning and configuration is simple but goes a long way when implemented well.

name: Apple AirPods Pro
crin_comments: Somewhat Diffuse-Field tuning with a smooth and natural midrange tonality.

name: JBL LIVE 300TWS
crin_comments: Kind of Harman-ish, but not. Heavy on the bass and sharp in the treble.

name: Bose SoundSport Free
crin_comments: Solid tonal balance with wide soundstage, though not the best in detailing.

name: Audiosense AQ3
crin_comments: Well-controlled bass despite the emphasis, limited by overall resolving ability.

name: ikko OH1
crin_comments: Well controlled sub-bass focus, high clarity and has an inherent "Asian" signature.

name: Shanling ME200
crin_comments: Slight mid-scoop going on. A little shouty, a little bassy, but not bad overall.

name: Fearless S4
crin_comments: Tonally accurate though can be a little heavy with its upper midrange.

name: Oriveti OH300
crin_comments: More similar than different to the OH500. Non-offensive tuning with decent technicalities.

name: Aune Jasper
crin_comments: A little shouty but overall a well-balanced tonality that's more pleasing than divisive.

name: BGVP DM7
crin_comments: Much more tonally-balanced take on the popular DM6.

name: Itsfit R3
crin_comments: Similar to the lauded UERM, but without its resolution nor sparkle.

name: DUNU DK-4001
crin_comments: A little shrill with slight cutbacks in tone compared to the DK-3001 Pro.

name: AAW AXH (2019)
crin_comments: Sharp treble though not to the point of being piercing. Decent rendition of the bright-neutral signature.

name: Unique Melody MacBeth
crin_comments: Extremely clear but may be too thin for some.

name: Elysian Artemis V2
crin_comments: A detailed, somewhat neutral-sounding IEM that should fit most people's tastes.

name: Acoustune HS1655Cu
crin_comments: Deep V-shape signature with some odd treble spikes; very Acoustune.

name: Acoustune HS1657
crin_comments: Deep V-shape signature with some odd treble spikes; very Acoustune.

name: Acoustune HS1677
crin_comments: Deep V-shape signature with some odd treble spikes; very Acoustune.

name: Beyerdynamic Xelento
crin_comments: Like the T8iE, with a little more treble and upper mids.

name: Shanling ME700 Lite
crin_comments: Rather radical change from the original ME700; far less warm with more upper-mid emphasis.

name: Kinera Nanna
crin_comments: Surprisingly well-extended for an EST implementation; somewhat blunted notes overall.

name: Lime Ears Aether
crin_comments: Excellent clarity and tone but marred slightly by slightly lackluster resolution

name: Sony MH755
crin_comments: Clean notes, proper sub-bass extension and a tonal balance beyond expectations.

name: Sony MDR-AS800AP
crin_comments: Extremely well-balanced tuning but with unfortunately middling technicalities.

name: Dita Fidelity
crin_comments: The more technical and less natural sounding of the Dita twins.

name: Vision Ears EVE 20
crin_comments: Solid technicalities in tandem with an uninspired tuning.

name: Empire Ears Valkyrie
crin_comments: Lots of sub-bass with extremely thin mids. Adequate technicalities.

name: Empire Ears Valkyrie Mk2
crin_comments: Not too dissimilar to its predecessor.

name: DUNU Titan 3
crin_comments: A more reined-in variant of the Titan 3's sound, more peaky but also slightly more resolving.

name: Shozy & Neo BG
crin_comments: Well balanced tuning with decent resolution, though suffers from slight timbral issues.

name: DUNU DK-2001
crin_comments: Slightly warm-tilted with a bit of treble spiciness.

name: TRI Starshine
crin_comments: A good example of "too much of a good thing": treble extension. Sibilance issues abound, but otherwise fine.

name: Gaudio Clariden
crin_comments: Somewhat reminiscent of a more mid-y Andromeda, though with extra wonkiness.

name: Fearless S6Rui
crin_comments: Similar to the S4/S5H though with smoother upper mids and treble response.

name: Sony XBA-A3
crin_comments: Coherent hybrid with a warm-ish tilt to its tone.

name: ThieAudio Legacy 9 (L9)
crin_comments: Bass a little too slow and sluggish with minor quirks in the midrange-treble transition.

name: NocturnaL Atlantis
crin_comments: Reference signature with immense clarity and energy.

name: Sony XBA-Z5
crin_comments: All-rounder. Somewhat neutral both in FR and tonality.

name: PEARS SH2
crin_comments: An odd take on neutrality but not the worst.

name: Fidue A91 "Sirius"
crin_comments: Uniquely tuned hybrid. Not very powerful DD bass with Diffuse-Field midrange.

name: Unique Melody Miracle V2
crin_comments: Slight downsloping signature with a treble spike for sparkle.

name: Soranik Ion
crin_comments: Clearly inspired by the 334, follows the same strengths in female vocals

name: Noble Tux 5
crin_comments: Deep, sub-bass focus with potentially sibilant treble. Scooped midrange.

name: Sony XBA-H3
crin_comments: Coherent hybrid with a warm-ish tilt to its tone. Similar to the XBA-A3.

name: ThieAudio Legacy 5 (L5)
crin_comments: A little lacking in the upper-mids but otherwise a competent set.

name: Anthem Five E4
crin_comments: The all-rounder; nothing stands out but nothing sounds terrible either. Safe, but perhaps too safe.

name: ARC Mira
crin_comments: A well-tuned basic setup with strengths in versatility.

name: Final Audio B3
crin_comments: Probably the best tuned of Final's B-series. Reminiscent of the E-series with BA characteristics.

name: Vision Ears VE3.2
crin_comments: Almost VE8-like in tonality, but lacks its technical abilities.

name: HUM Reference
crin_comments: Basically sounds like a shallow-fit ER4S.

name: Westone ES60
crin_comments: Great timbre and well-tuned, held back by its resolution

name: Custom Art FIBAE 7
crin_comments: Neutral tuning with a more relaxed top end. Probably the best-tuned Custom Art.

name: qdc Dmagic
crin_comments: Probably the best triple-DD IEM out there by virtue of not being a hot mess tonally.

name: Aure Flame
crin_comments: A little better managed than the Elixir but not a massive improvement. Reminds me of a budget FH5.

name: Acoustune HS1551
crin_comments: Warm and smooth tonality with a pleasing tuning not many would hate.

name: Empire Ears EVR
crin_comments: A nicely tuned flat-ish signature with good technical ability all around.

name: Sennheiser IE800
crin_comments: Good bass with shimmery treble. Downsloping response with slightly wonky tonality.

name: Aroma Witch Girl S
crin_comments: Pretty good technicalities but with a rather generic tuning.

name: FiR VxV
crin_comments: Interested coloured take on a neutral reference signature. A little uneven in the mids.

name: Sennheiser IE800S
crin_comments: Very subtle refinement to the original IE800.

name: Campfire Solaris (SE)
crin_comments: Coherent and well balanced hybrid though with slight midrange hollowness.

name: FitEar Private 333
crin_comments: Very exciting and sharp signature. Fatiguing and not for everyone.

name: Dita Dream XLS
crin_comments: Standard Dita house sound with a non-standard bass roll-off. Decent, not amazing.

name: Unique Melody Maven
crin_comments: Decently resolving, decent tonality; not bad, not amazing.

name: Aroma Witch Girl W12
crin_comments: Warm response balanced out by a sparkly treble emphasis; good technicalities, if a little narrow-sounding.

name: 64 Audio A4t
crin_comments: Good tonal balance but lacking in definition and low-level detailing

name: Acoustune HS1697
crin_comments: A little wonkier than your average Acoustune but still retains the signature V-shape.

name: Campfire Ara
crin_comments: Very resolving set of IEMs, triggers the "uncanny valley" effect with its tuning.

name: Jomo Tango
crin_comments: Deep V-shape signature with a warm tilt; good technicalities.

name: Aroma Ace
crin_comments: Really odd take on neutrality. Not the worst... but it's not natural by any means.

name: DUNU Titan 1
crin_comments: Bright, almost DF-ish in tonality. Shouty but with open imaging and decent detail.

name: Audio Technica ATH-LS200
crin_comments: Somewhat Diffuse-Field neutral with its own quirks. Good technical ability.

name: Fearless S5H
crin_comments: Similar if not identical to the S4, though with a little less upper mids.

name: Sennheiser IE400 Pro
crin_comments: Heavy bass boost balanced out by good treble energy along with decent midrange tonality.

name: InEar StageDiver SD-2
crin_comments: As with most GQ setups: well-balanced, excellent tuning and decent technical ability.

name: FiiO FA9
crin_comments: More of a downslope-neutral kind of tonality. A bit above average as far as technical performance goes.

name: Oriveti OH500
crin_comments: More similar than different to the OH300. Non-offensive tuning with decent technicalities.

name: ARC Oculus
crin_comments: Relaxing, warm signature with sub-par resolving ability.

name: Ultimate Ears UE6 Pro
crin_comments: A capable hybrid with little weaknesses.

name: TRI Starlight
crin_comments: Painful sibilance due to uncontrolled upper treble.

name: Clear Tune Monitors CT-6E
crin_comments: Good, well-balanced tonality though falls apart from the treble upwards.

name: Stealthsonics U9 JDM
crin_comments: Does away with the timbre issues of the standard U9.

name: Meze Rai Penta
crin_comments: Pleasing tonality with subpar technical ability.

name: Elysian Cora (2019)
crin_comments: A decent hybrid weird slightly odd midrange tonality.

name: FitEar TG334
crin_comments: Like the MH334 with quite a bit less treble

name: Rhapsodio Solar
crin_comments: An all-rounder to a fault. Truly a master of none.

name: FitEar MH334
crin_comments: Perfect for female vocals, but otherwise quite coloured

name: Aure Elixir
crin_comments: Sort of wonky-but-not tonality that reminds me of some of Audiosense's weird IEMs.

name: Soranik Bastille Signature
crin_comments: Upper-mid and sub-bass forward, mids are scooped and can get hollow.

name: Etymotic ER2SE/ER2XR
crin_comments: Slightly less detailed than the ER4, but without the usual BA timbre.

name: Samsung Galaxy Buds2 Pro
crin_comments: A less shouty interpretation of Harman with the same controlled yet impactful bass response.

name: AKG N400
crin_comments: Does away with the timbral issues of the Buds+ and sets itself as a superior.

name: Samsung Galaxy Buds Pro
crin_comments: More lower mids than your average Harman-tuned IEM, but works in its favour by being more pleasant.

name: Apple AirPods Pro 2
crin_comments: A more exciting sound signature in comparison to its predecessor, with little in terms of drawbacks.

name: Etymotic ER3SE/ER3XR
crin_comments: An ER4 with a bit less treble and upper extension.

name: Unique Melody 2HT âTerminatorâ
crin_comments: Tonality almost reminds me of a HYLA hybrid. Well tuned with strong technical performance.

name: qdc 4SS
crin_comments: High clarity, high resolution reference-type monitor with spot-on tone.

name: Fearless S8Z
crin_comments: Solid all-rounder with a safe, pleasing tuning.

name: iBasso AM05
crin_comments: Well-balanced tonality, slightly tilted towards brightness. Probably the best iBasso IEM yet.

name: Fearless S6Pro
crin_comments: Technical tuning with very forward detailing.

name: HYLA CE-5
crin_comments: Probably the best bass response I've ever heard. Thin-ish midrange that sounds unnatural on certain instruments.

name: HYLA Sarda
crin_comments: Standard "HYLA" house sound, doesn't do much different from the CE-5 and TE-5B.

name: HYLA TE-5B
crin_comments: Similar to the CE-5 though ever-so-slightly thinner in the midrange.

name: qdc 8SH
crin_comments: Tonally, a slightly wonkier variation of the top-tier qdc IEMs.

name: Jomo Trinity SS
crin_comments: Highly detailed, well separated imaging though severely lacking in treble extension.

name: Unique Melody Mason V3+
crin_comments: Decent resolution, nothing really special otherwise.

name: Tanchjim Oxygen
crin_comments: One of the best-tuned DDs tuned somewhat to Harman. Defined and detailed.

name: Sennheiser IE900
crin_comments: Well-resolving DD IEM with excellent treble control, though with somewhat weak mid-high harmonics.

name: Noble Khan
crin_comments: Clean yet lean, solid low-end rumble but treble get splashy. Technical but lacking naturalness.

name: Gaudio Nair
crin_comments: Well-tuned neutral monitor bottlenecked by timbre and resolution.

name: Ultimate Ears Reference Remastered (UERR)
crin_comments: Warm with good tonality. Good all-rounder albeit definitely not a reference signature.

name: Vision Ears VE7
crin_comments: Fairly inoffensive tuning with solid technicalities.

name: Unique Melody MEST
crin_comments: A smooth, relaxing listen (in custom form) backed up with good technicalities.

name: Unique Melody MEST Mk2
crin_comments: Pretty much the same as the Mk1, though with extra sub-bass presence.

name: Elysian Hades V2
crin_comments: Upper-mid forward signature with intense upper treble response.

name: Elysian Terminator V2
crin_comments: A more intense, upper-mid forward Terminator V1 with the same level of technical ability.

name: Elysian Terminator
crin_comments: Well rounded smooth signature that doesn't offend.

name: DUNU DK-3001 Pro
crin_comments: Well-tuned and coherent. Does little wrong and very easy to like.

name: DUNU x Z Reviews SA6 Ultra
Hidition NT6 Pro
crin_comments: A V-shaped version of the NT6. The change in tuning kills the technical ability slightly

name: 64 Audio A18S
crin_comments: Warning: the demo unit does not sound like the custom. Demos are sub-bass focused while customs are warm.

name: InEar Prophile-8
crin_comments: Very "studio" like sound, heavy priority on technicalities if a little dead-sounding.

name: Audeze Euclid
crin_comments: Certainly far better tuned than its predecessors with the same excellent technicalities.

name: Jomo Flamenco
crin_comments: Tuned to be more pleasing and tonally accurate compared to the old Flamenco at the cost of sheer detail.

name: iBasso IT04
crin_comments: A nice improvement over the IT03 though midrange hollowness still exists.

name: JQ Hua Jiang
crin_comments: Somewhat subdued and "safe" tuning with decent resolving ability.

name: Oriolus MK2
crin_comments: Lively yet non-fatiguing hybrid experience.

name: FiR M3
crin_comments: Interesting tubeless technology, though the imaging improvements are minimal.

name: 64 Audio N8
crin_comments: Sub-bass focus, rich and smooth yet relatively neutral in tone.

name: FiR M4
crin_comments: Too similar to the M3 to be worth the price markup.

name: FitEar MH334SR
crin_comments: A MH334 with more treble extension and more opened imaging.

name: FiR M5
crin_comments: Warmer than the M3 and M4 with lower resolution.

name: Mofasest M14
crin_comments: Essentially a more tonally "correct" version of the ThieAudio V14.

name:
Hidition Viento
(B-mode, custom)
crin_comments: Best-in-class tuning and tonal balance with near-perfect coherency. Recommended as a custom-fit.
